You have not told us anything about those `NakedQuad` and `HiddenSingle` thingies, but from the way you are using them they appear to be classes. But judging by the capitalization you use, (if we presume you use standard-conforming capitalization,) the `getHint(...)` methods you are invoking on them are `static` methods.

Perhaps this way of doing things made sense while learning the basics, but now with inheritance you have to up your game.

The first thing you have to do is to turn these methods into *instance* methods instead of static.  This is done by removing the `static` keyword. Then, in order to invoke those methods, you are going to need instances.  So, you cannot be invoking `NakedSingle.getHint(...)` anymore, you are going to have to do `NakedSingle nakedSingle = new NakedSingle();` and then `nakedSingle.getHint(...)`. 

Once you have done that, everything should still work. 

Now, to reduce the amount of code, you have two options:

1. Introduce an `interface Thingie` declaring a `getHint( ... )` method, and make all those thingies implement that interface, (`class NakedSingle implements Thingie`,) each providing its own implementation of that method.

2. Introduce a common base `class Thingie` declaring a `getHint( ... )` abstract method, and make each of those thingies extend that abstract class (`class NakedSingle extends Thingie`) each providing its own implementation of that method.

