You seem to be on the right track with the odd and even. Was that a hint that was given to you?

You need to make use of the fact that `b^(x+y) == b^x * b^y`

You are currently splitting exp into `1` and `exp-1`, and using the those two values as your x and y.

But, that is the slowest possible way to do it. Choose numbers that are closer together.  Such as `exp / 2` and `exp - exp/2`  (assuming truncation). Of course, you need a special case for exp = 1 in that case.

EDIT:
Your question is really about algorithms. Why 10 calls when it could be fewer? Somebody told you it can be done in 5, and it can.

so, here we go in pseudo code, mostly because this is a fun algorithm to explore.

```
pow(base, exp) {

  if (exp == 0) return 1;
  else if (isOdd(exp)) {
    var val = pow(base, (exp - 1)/2);
    return base * val * val;
  } 
  else {
    var val = pow(base, exp/2);
    return val * val;
  }
}
```

Technically, the first call is not a recursive call.  
A call from within the method is a recursive call.

So, initializing `count` with `-1` will reduce that initial increment.

If it helps, try printing out the values for each call; it might provide a better visual of the process.

```java
static int count = -1;
static double power(double base, int exp) {
    count++;
    if (count != 0) System.out.printf(&quot;call %,d, exp= %,d%n&quot;, count, exp);
    return exp != 0 ? base * power(base, --exp) : 1;
}
```

You need to be a little more careful with your `power()` method. Compare this slightly different version of your method with your own, and compare it to the recursive definition you&#39;ve been provided.

&gt;  1. x&lt;sup&gt;0&lt;/sup&gt; = 1
&gt;  2. x&lt;sup&gt;n&lt;/sup&gt; = x * x&lt;sup&gt;n-1&lt;/sup&gt; for n odd, n&gt;0
&gt;  3. x&lt;sup&gt;n&lt;/sup&gt; = (x&lt;sup&gt;n / 2&lt;/sup&gt;)&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;, n even, n&gt;0

```java
public class Power1 {
    public static int count = 0;
    static double power(double base, int exp) {
        count++;
        // base case:
        if (exp == 0)
            return 1;

       if ((exp % 2) == 1) {
           return base * power(base, exp - 1);
       } else {
           double squareRoot = power(base, exp / 2);
           return squareRoot * squareRoot;
       }
    }
}
```

